{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15148"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15148"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.7,0.04,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60314"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7836"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19106"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60314"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn epidemiologist is studying a cluster of encephalitis cases in rural Bangladesh. The outbreak occurred among date palm sap collectors and their families. Patients typically presented with fever and myalgia, progressing to confusion and brainstem dysfunction over several days. The case fatality rate was 75%. Laboratory testing confirmed Nipah virus infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following animals is most likely to be the natural reservoir host of this virus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Domestic pigs","Fruit bats","Domestic chickens","Wild rodents","Domestic cats"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis outbreak investigation presents typical epidemiological features of Nipah virus infection. Understanding the natural reservoir is crucial for implementing effective control measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFruit bats\u003C/strong\u003E (flying foxes) are the natural reservoir hosts for Nipah virus. These fruit bats contaminate date palm sap with their saliva and excreta while feeding, leading to human infections when the raw sap is consumed. They can carry the virus without becoming ill themselves, a characteristic feature of a natural reservoir host.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDomestic pigs\u003C/strong\u003E can act as intermediate amplifying hosts in some Nipah virus outbreaks, particularly in Southeast Asia. However, they are not the natural reservoir. The virus likely spreads to pigs when they consume fruit contaminated by infected bat saliva or urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDomestic chickens\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in Nipah virus transmission. While they can be hosts for other viruses like avian influenza, they do not play a role in the Nipah virus ecosystem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWild rodents\u003C/strong\u003E are not known to be involved in Nipah virus transmission. While they can be reservoirs for other zoonotic diseases, such as hantavirus, they are not implicated in Nipah virus ecology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDomestic cats\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in Nipah virus transmission. While they can be infected with some zoonotic diseases, they are not known to play any role in Nipah virus ecology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fruit bats (flying foxes) are the natural reservoir host for Nipah virus.","Pigs can act as intermediate amplifying hosts in some Nipah virus outbreaks.","Understanding viral reservoirs is crucial for preventing transmission and controlling outbreaks."],"references":["Ang BSP, Lim TCC, Wang L. Nipah Virus Infection. J Clin Microbiol. 2018;56(6):e01875-17. Published 2018 May 25. doi:10.1128/JCM.01875-17"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15148"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T21:12:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T21:13:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7836"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60314"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bas